\sum The famous legend of crafty Kpwat and his brothers against the Ogre.
\in
\nt
\gl Légende
\sta Eng-trans_no
\sta intro_no
\ord 06

\rf Lkn.Qat.001
\tv Mok suusuu pule maraw ēn qētēg m̄ērē heg.
\ta °°Here is how my story begins.
\rf Lkn.Qat.002
\tv Suusuu pule maraw heg avan moomä king avan m̄o, hahan i Qat.
\ta This is the story of our former King, called Kpwat.
\rf Lkn.Qat.003
\tv Älähä nē 'n tasun̄ mon too qatuu ak.
\ta This is the story of how he carved himself a huge canoe.
\rf Lkn.Qat.004
\tv On too qēn̄, Qat ēn van hag, tē tärä tul too qatuu qētē nanaa, sa ga mäkä ak
mē.
\ta One day, Kpwat went to the bush, and chopped down a large rosewood tree
(Pterocarpus indicus) to make himself a canoe.
\rf Lkn.Qat.005
\tv Nē 'n tärä va#van, nē 'n sēv, on rävräv nē tē mulä.
\ta He chopped at it so much that it fell down; then evening came, and he returned
back home.
\rf Lkn.Qat.006
\tv Nē 'n n̄oo, on matpäh, nē 'n van tägäh hag: nanaa nen̄ ēn tuu ajew lēh nok.
\ta He went to sleep, and on the next day, went back to the bush – but the tree in
question was standing there again! 
\rf Lkn.Qat.007
\tv Nē tē tärä lēh.
\ta So he started to chop it again.
\rf Lkn.Qat.008
\tv Tärä tärä tärä va#van, nē 'n sēv, nē tē mulä.
\ta He chopped it on and on and on until it fell; then he went back home.
\rf Lkn.Qat.009
\tv Van, n̄oo, on matpäh nē 'n van ajew tägäh lēh hag: nanaa ēn tuu ajew lēh
nok.
\ta After a night at home, on the morning he walked back up to the bush – but the tree
was standing up there once again!
\rf Lkn.Qat.010
\tv Nē tē tärä lēh. Vag-tēl gēn ek.
\ta So he went on to cut it down again. That was now the third time!
\rf Lkn.Qat.011
\tv Tärä tärä va#van, nē 'n sēv, nē tē mulä.
\ta He chopped it down, felled it, and went back home.
\rf Lkn.Qat.012
\tv On matpäh nē 'n row tägäh hag, nanaa ēn tuu ajew lēh nok.
\ta On the next morning he dashed back up to the bush, and saw the tree standing
there once again!
\rf Lkn.Qat.013
\tv Alē, nē sa “Ta! Noknok heg, na ga 'ēv woo to have heg, na ga ätä tuwoo sē
gēn tē vaavaatuu lōk lēh nanaa na ok ēn tärä sēv!”
\nt pronounced /nanaa na 'k ē ~ na 'k ēn tärä sēv/
\ta “Alright!” he thought, “This time, I'm going to hide somewhere here, and watch to
figure out who has been standing back up that tree I keep trying to chop down!”
\pc *
\rf Lkn.Qat.014
\tv Nē 'n 'ēv, nē 'n 'ätä woo we i Wēmarawraw tē ät ma. Too vuu, hahan i
Wēmarawraw.
\ta So off he went to hide, and as he watched out, suddenly Butterfly appeared. It was
a god, called Butterfly.
\nt translate as "Butterfly"??  or keep as "Wēmarawraw"??
\rf Lkn.Qat.015
\tv Nē 'n 'ēv, nē 'n petn̄äg too m̄asgi nanaa nē ok ēn tärä sēv ak, tē petn̄äg too
m̄asgi, tē 'ēv mē.
\ta So Kpwat was hiding, holding a piece of wood from the tree he had been chopping
down into a canoe: he had taken away that piece and gone into hiding.
\rf Lkn.Qat.016
\tv Wēmarawraw nen̄ ēn row ma, ēn pahav lōk lēh ēn qētqētē nanaa nen̄ va#van,
\ta As soon as he had landed in, Butterfly began to assemble back together the trunk
of the rosewood tree. 
\rf Lkn.Qat.017
\tv nē tē tuu ajew lōk lēh, nē tē äm too m̄asgi gēn nen̄ Qat ok ēn petn̄äg.
\ta He stood it up again, and started looking for that last piece which Kpwat had
hidden away.
\rf Lkn.Qat.018
\tv Nē gēn tē äm gēn ek!
\ta There he was now, searching everywhere!
\rf Lkn.Qat.019
\tv Äm, ēn äm, ēn äm va#van, nē tē vaavuh sa “Ēy! Sē wōn have heg ēn petn̄äg
too m̄asgi nanaa heg, nē a siivä mun na!”
\ta Butterfly searched on and on: “Hey!” he exclaimed “Whoever hid a piece of this tree
somewhere, I wish they brought it back to me!”
\rf Lkn.Qat.020
\tv We Qat tē haläqäg jen le gawon.
\nt ... ou /häläqäg/
\ta And suddenly Kpwat leapt out from the bushes.
\rf Lkn.Qat.021
\tv Haläqäg ma mēn mon tälä, sa “A, nēk gēn nen̄, nēk ok tē vaavaatuu lōk lēh
nanaa na ok ēn tē tärä sēv? Na gēn ga vuh nēk noknok heg le!”
\nt /noknok heg/ or /noknokheg/ ??
\ta “Ha ha!” he exclaimed, brandishing his axe, “So that was you! You were the one
who kept standing back this rosewood tree every time I chopped it down? I'm
killing you right now!”
\rf Lkn.Qat.022
\tv Alē, Wēmarawraw sa “Ta, nēk mētē vuh lee na! Na a pirin̄ nēk. Wōjō a tärä lōk
lēh ēn ak nen̄.”
\ta “Mercy!” cried Butterfly, “Don't kill me! I will help you. You and I will start your
canoe again!”
\rf Lkn.Qat.023
\tv Wōrō tē tärä lōk lēh.
\ta So they resumed their work again.
\rf Lkn.Qat.024
\tv Tärä va#van, ēn sēv, †wōrō tē wok /† wōrō tē tasun̄.
\ta They chopped the tree down, and began to carve it.
\rf Lkn.Qat.025
\tv Tasun̄ va#van ēn pah, wōrō tē vivih, tē ruruh to lē naw.
\ta When they finished carving the canoe, they tied the pieces together, and finally
dragged the canoe down to the sea.
\pc *  *
\rf Lkn.Qat.026
\tv We Qat tē van tē vis mun tuutuan. Tuutuan nen̄ gaprä tuwa jēm̄ēn tuwa.
\nt I hear a long vowel /tuutuan/ (?)
\nt he actually said “Tutuan nen̄ lavōrō.” = 7;  but corrected himself during transcription.  [BG4-36a]
\ta Then Kpwat went back to his brothers. He had eleven of them.
\rf Lkn.Qat.028
\tv Van, vis mun gēē sa “Ōh! Mok qatuu ak nok ēhē! Noknok heg, gēj a maēs a
van have, gēj a van ēs gēn ek.”
\nt start [BG4-36b]
\ta “Brothers!” he told them, “I now own an immense canoe! From now on, we'll be
able to go wherever we like!”
\rf Lkn.Qat.029
\tv We wēē tuutuan nen̄ ēn ron̄ we gēē tē gäl nē.
\ta As they heard him, his brothers decided to trick him.
\rf Lkn.Qat.030
\tv Sa “Gēj a van vēgēn gangēj qawōō?”
\ta “Let's go pick up some almonds, shall we?” they proposed.
\rf Lkn.Qat.031
\tv Gēē tē van hag lē qētē qawōō nen̄, sa “Sē gēn a vēgēn gēn ek?”
\ta Once they had walked all the way up to the canarium trees, Kpwat asked “Alright,
so who's climbing first?”
\rf Lkn.Qat.032
\tv Gēē sa “Nēk! Nēk a vēgēn!”
\ta “You!” they replied, “You climb first!”
\rf Lkn.Qat.033
\tv We Qat tē vēgēn.
\ta So Kpwat climbed the tree.
\rf Lkn.Qat.034
\tv Nē 'n vēgēn jēn̄ to hag nen̄, we †an̄ä nen̄ tē rēg /† qētē qawōō nen̄ tē rēg.
\nt noté /en̄e/, je corrige… de toute façon, erreur pour /qawôô/
\ta But as he reached the top of the tree, suddenly the canarium tree began to swell up!
\rf Lkn.Qat.035
\tv Too sē jen gēē ēn mänäg qētē qawōō nen̄, qētē qawōō tē rēg, Qat ga hēw ēs
avōh.
\ta One of the brothers had cast a spell on the tree so it would swell up, and make
Kpwat unable to come back down.
\rf Lkn.Qat.036
\tv Alē, gēē tē van, gēē tē toto jen nē nē tē hag make qaawōō.
\nq /qaawōō/ ou /qawōō/?? /jen/ ou /jēn/??
\ta Suddenly they took off and ran away from him, while he remained stuck on top of
that tree.
\pc *  *
\rf Lkn.Qat.037
\tv Gēē 'n van, ruruh mon ak, gēē tē sō.
\nt actual text = 2 Bislama loans
\ta They rushed to find his canoe, dragged it out to the sea and began paddling.
\rf Lkn.Qat.038
\tv Gēē tē sō jen Vanōlav, gēē a maēs sa gēē a sō to Lakon.
\nt actual text = got them reversed!
\ta They were paddling away from Vanua Lava, and wanted to reach Gaua.
\rf Lkn.Qat.039
\tv Qat tē hag maken va## van, nē 'n 'ätä woo we taqa tē kakal ma.
\ta As for Kpwat, he was still sitting on top of the tree, when he suddenly saw a spider
coming to him.
\rf Lkn.Qat.040
\tv Taqa ēn kakal ma, sa / nē sala “Ey! Tuak! Nēk ga pirin̄ ēs na?”
\ta As the spider came close, he said “Hey, my friend! Can you help me out?”
\rf Lkn.Qat.041
\tv Taqa sa “Ga wē, na ga pirin̄ ēs nēk.”
\ta – “Yes, said the spider, I can help you.”
\rf Lkn.Qat.042
\tv Alē, nē tē mäkä 'n tien jen make än̄ä / qawōō, tē row jēn̄ hōw lē tanē, lōk lēh
hag, nē 'n mäkä m̄ērē nen̄ va#van #
\ta So it started to spin its silk from the top of the almond tree, slid all the way down
to the ground, then back up, on and on and on #
\rf Lkn.Qat.043
\tv nē 'n lekteg kere haj on Qat ga vēgēn suusuu / a hēw suusuu, alē Qat tē hēw
suusuu ēn tie taqa nen̄.
\ta when the web became solid enough for Kpwat to clamber along, he followed the
spider's silk all the way to the ground.
\rf Lkn.Qat.044
\tv Jēn̄ hōw, ginteg tägäh hōw lē naw: mon ak gaiv nok!
\ta As soon as he touched down, he rushed towards the shore, and realised his canoe
had disappeared!
\rf Lkn.Qat.045
\tv Tuutuan ēn pal nok, mēn mon gamtō, mēn gamtō mon Qat gēē tē to me!
\ta His brothers had stolen it, and run away with his wife, Kpwat's wife! 
\rf Lkn.Qat.046
\tv Sa gēē a van me Lakon.
\nt actual text = said Vanōlav!
\ta They were on their way here, to Gaua.
\pc *
\rf Lkn.Qat.047
\tv We nē tē lä 'n too vinlah, nē tē row ol lolon, mēn ōjēn vätäl ga men, nē tē
hälä suusuu gēē.
\nt actual text = said /vin matu/, corrected himself
\ta Without further ado, Kpwat seized a coconut, and jumped inside. He had taken a
supply of sweet bananas, and began to drift on the sea behind them.
\rf Lkn.Qat.048
\tv Gēē 'n sō va# van, lē sēnē naw, gēē 'n 'ätä woo we, vinlah nen̄ tē hälä ma.
\ta As for them, they were travelling on their canoe, in the middle of the ocean, when
suddenly they took sight of a coconut that was drifting towards them.
\rf Lkn.Qat.049
\tv Hälä hälä van ma, rigtäg we nē tē gän too vätäl ga men, tē 'äqä 'n vinn̄i.
\ta As it was drifting closer and closer, Kpwat ate one of his sweet bananas, and threw
the skin away.
\rf Lkn.Qat.050
\tv Vinn̄i nē 'n hälä m̄o, tē 'äqä 'n vinn̄i, vinn̄i tē hälä ma.
\ta The banana skin he tossed away also began to drift towards the canoe.
\rf Lkn.Qat.051
\tv Gēē 'n van, 'ätä “Ey! Sē 'n gän vätäl ga men heg?”
\ta As soon as they saw it, they said “Hey! Who just ate this sweet banana?”
\rf Lkn.Qat.052
\tv Gēē a ron̄ avōh sa i Qat (va) la, Qat va nok lē vinlah.
\ta They had no idea this was really Kpwat, Kpwat who was hiding in the coconut.
\rf Lkn.Qat.053
\tv Hag va#van, gēē tē ätä vērēgēl avōh, nē 'n gän lēh too vätäl tē äqä lēh.
\ta So on they went, still bemused of what was happening. Then he ate a second
banana, and threw the skin away again.
\rf Lkn.Qat.054
\tv Gēē tē ätä vērēgēl vata avōh ni.
\ta Still, they did not understand who that was.
\rf Lkn.Qat.055
\tv Nē tē hälä m̄o. Van, jēn̄ to Lakon #
\ta On and on they drifted, until they were in sight of Gaua.
\rf Lkn.Qat.056
\tv Nē 'n hälä hag m̄ērē nen̄ we, gēē tē sō rigtäg nē päh, gēē tē lä 'n vinlah nen̄.
Lä hōw lē ak, gēē tē van.
\ta As he was still drifting like this, they pulled their canoe closer, and seized the
coconut. They took it in their canoe, and went on.
\rf Lkn.Qat.058
\tv Gēē 'n gih tē m̄ērē heg we nē tē wisis!
\ta As they were holding it in their hands, Kpwat inside suddenly broke wind!
\rf Lkn.Qat.059
\tv Puni tē ah we gēē tē äqä wutä nē.
\ta The smell made them toss the coconut away.
\rf Lkn.Qat.060
\tv We gēē tē sō va#van, jēn̄ ma Lakon.
\ta So on they went, closer and closer till they reached Gaua.
\nt the 2 sentences that follow is a later addition 
\rf Lkn.Qat.061
\tv Qat nē 'n jēn̄ m̄o nok salēn, nē tē vēgēn make vaj tē hag jērē gēē.
\ta But Kpwat had reached the shores already: he had climbed a pandanus tree and was
waiting for his brothers there.
\rf Lkn.Qat.062
\tv Gēē 'n sō ma, jēn̄ lē en, nē 'n häläqäg sēwēl tē saqal worä mon ak mēn mon
tälä.
\ta No sooner had they landed on the beach than he jumped down from the tree, and
destroyed his own canoe with his axe.
\rf Lkn.Qat.063
\tv Nē sala “Gamu 'n 'ätä vinn̄i vätäl nen̄ tē hälä ma?” Gēē sa “Aa!”.
\ta He asked them “Did you see the banana skin that was floating on the sea? — Yes,”
they replied.
\rf Lkn.Qat.064
\tv Nē sa “Na nen̄!” # “To nēk ēn row kēl make naha ma heg?”
\ta “Well, he added, that was me! — But how did you even get here?!”
\rf Lkn.Qat.065
\tv Nē sa “Vinlah! Gamu ok ēn äqä wutä nen̄, na nen̄! Na lē vinlah nen̄.”
\nt actual text = said /äqä wutä *na* nen̄/, corrected himself
\ta “Aboard a coconut!” he replied, “You remember the one you threw away? well, that
was me. I was in that coconut.”
\rf Lkn.Qat.066
\tv We gēē tē van ajew hag le vanō.
\nt actual text = said Vanōlav!
\ta So they began to walk inland to find a village.
\pc *  * 
\rf Lkn.Qat.067
\tv Van, gēē tē n̄oo mēn too qatuu ätmät.
\ta They found a place to sleep, at the house of a giant ogre.
\rf Lkn.Qat.068
\tv N̄oo mun nē, ätmät nen̄ ēn 'ätä gēē, nē sa “Ha'ēh! Noknok heg, gamu ga n̄oo
vaan heg lē too um̄ä heg, na na a n̄oo päh heg.”
\ta As soon as he had seen them, the ogre had invited them to stay with him: “Alright,
he said, tonight you will all sleep over here in this house of mine; as for me, I'll sleep
over there.”
\rf Lkn.Qat.069
\tv La nē ok tē gäl woo gēē to sa nē ok a vuh gēē.
\ta But he was really fooling them, with a plan to kill them.
\rf Lkn.Qat.070
\tv On qēn̄, nē 'n row ma, Qat ēn sirin̄ ēn valakärän lē sini um̄ä, gēē pah gēē tē
row ol lē valakärän nen̄ gēē tē n̄oo lolon.
\nt … Qat ēn { jej || sirin̄ } ēn {pos || valakärän} lē sini um̄ä, …
\ta And indeed, that same night he set off towards that room – but Kpwat had already
flicked open the central pillar of the house, and they had all walked inside to sleep
there.
\rf Lkn.Qat.071
\tv Tan̄ro nen̄ ēn row ma on qēn̄, row ma, äm gēē, gēē gaiv. Gēē va lē valakärän.
\na note that /ätmät/ is here equated with /tan̄ro/!
\ta So when the evil spirit came in during the night, he searched for them everywhere,
but could not find them. They were hiding in the central pillar!
\pc *
\rf Lkn.Qat.072
\tv On matpäh nē 'n row ma, nē sa: “Ey! Tuutuak! Na 'n row ma on qēn̄, gamu
gaiv, gamu have?”
\ta The next morning, he came in and asked them: “My friends! I came here during the
night, but I couldn't find you: where were you?”
\rf Lkn.Qat.073
\tv La too tuan Qat nen̄ nē ok ga sa, nē ok a visvis on viivirin̄ ga 'ēv'ēv m̄ērē ek.
\ta Now one of Kpwat's brothers was a bit stupid, and would always tell away secrets
like this one.
\rf Lkn.Qat.074
\tv Nē sa “O! Nēk ēn row ma nen̄, gamä 'n 'ēv woo lē valakärän lē sini um̄ä hegi!”
\nt I should remove all apostrophes for glottal stops!?
\ta “Of course, he replied. When you came to visit us, we were all hiding in this pillar, in
the middle of your house!
\rf Lkn.Qat.075
\tv Tan̄ro sa “Ha'ēh! Ga wē!”
\ta – Oh, really?” said the ogre. “Perfect!”
\pc *
\rf Lkn.Qat.076
\tv Gēē tē van lēh lē m̄as, lä lēh gängän ma, wälwäl gängän pah, sa: “Ha'ōh! Gamu
't n̄oo lēh!” Gēē tē n̄oo.
\ta Then they went back to the garden, picked some food again, came back to bake it.
“Alright,” he said, “It's time you went back to sleep!” and off they went to sleep.
\rf Lkn.Qat.077
\tv On qēn̄, nē 'n row tägäh lēh ma, sa a gän gēē, Qat ēn mäkä gēē 'n n̄oo lē gah.
Gah avan um̄ä.
\ta During the night, the ogre quickly came back again to kill them, but this time Kpwat
had made them sleep in the roof.
\rf Lkn.Qat.078
\tv Nē 'n jej gah mēn pisliman m̄ērē heg, gah tē wät gēē tē row ol lolon, gēē tē
n̄oo.
\ta He had hit one of the rafters with a flick of his fingers like this, and suddenly the
bamboo had split open, allowing them to jump inside and spend the night there.
\rf Lkn.Qat.079
\tv Tan̄ro 'n row tägäh ma, äm tägäh gēē, gēē gaiv.
\ta As the ogre rushed in, he began to seek them, but could not find them.
\rf Lkn.Qat.080
\tv On matpäh, nē 'n row ma nē sa, “Eh! Gēē wēē tuutuak! Na 'n row ma on qēn̄
sa gēj a suusuu, na 'n row tägäh ma, gamu gaiv!”
\nt should write /gēē wēē +N/ as one or 2 words??
\ta The next morning, he came back and asked “Hey, my friends! I came here during the
night so we could have a chat, but when I looked for you, you were nowhere to be
found!”
\rf Lkn.Qat.081
\tv We tuan Qat nen̄ ti vis mun nē sa: “O, nēk ēn row ma nen̄, i Qat ēn petn̄äg
gamä lē gah! Gamä 'n n̄oo woo lē gah.”
\ta So Kpwat's brother replied: “Well, when you came in, Kpwat had just hidden us in
the rafters! We were just sleeping in the roof.”
\rf Lkn.Qat.082
\tv Tan̄ro nen̄ sa: “Ha'ēh!” Nē tē van lōk lēh.
\ta “Oh I see!” replied the ogre, and off he went.
\pc *
\rf Lkn.Qat.083
\tv Gēē tē wälwäl, gängän lēh, on rävräv gēn nen̄, nē sa: “Alē, gamu 't n̄oo!”
\ta That day they did some cooking again, had dinner together, and when the evening
came, he told them again “Alright, time you went to sleep!”
\rf Lkn.Qat.084
\tv On qēn̄ nē tē row lōk lēh ma.
\ta And during the night, he came in once again.
\rf Lkn.Qat.085
\tv Row lōk lēh ma nen̄: äm tägäh gēē, jej tägäh gah, gēē gaiv lolon.
\ta And as he came back in, he began looking for them; he tried to hit the rafters, but
they were not inside.
\rf Lkn.Qat.086
\tv La gēē va 'n n̄oo makē wolwol.
\ta This time, they had all gone to sleep in the (crossbeam).
\rf Lkn.Qat.087
\tv On matpäh nē 'n row lōk lēh ma, tuan Qat nen̄ sa / nē sala: “Ēh, wēē tuutuak!
Na 'n row ma on qēn̄ sa gēj ga suusuu, gamu gaiv!”
\rf Lkn.Qat.088
\tv We tuan Qat nen̄ sa: “Oh, nēk ēn row ma nen̄, i Qat ēn petn̄äg gamä lē
wolwol maken heg, gamä 'n n̄oo maken heg.” Sa “Ha'ēh!”
\rf Lkn.Qat.089
\tv We talōw avan ēhē nen̄, gēē gēn tē wälwäl lēh to nen̄, Qat sa: “Wēē tuutuak,
na tē mäkä kere gēj to, la gamu tē visvis jērē gēj to, noknok heg gēj ga to' lōk
lēh gēn ek!”
\nt [intermède]
\rf Lkn.Qat.090
\tv Sa “Noknok heg, na tē petn̄äg kere gēj to, gamu tē 'en vis on gēj to; ak, ēn
manreg nok. Noknok heg gēj a mulä lēh älähä?”
\pc *  *
\nt 12'25"
\rf Lkn.Qat.091
\tv Alē, nē sa: “Noknok heg, gēj a wälwäl, gēē 'n wälwäl hōw, naw gaiv. E! Too sē
row vil naw!”
\nt /row vil/ = van goy= go fetch
\ta
\rf Lkn.Qat.092
\tv Alē, too tuan Qat tē van.
\nt one of Q's companions went off
\ta
\rf Lkn.Qat.093
\tv Qat vis mun nē sa “Nēk a van, qis manreg mon̄ pō nēk tē vēgēn makē ram̄os.”
\rf Lkn.Qat.094
\tv To tuan ēn van hōw, qis manreg mon pō, row vēgēn makē ram̄os, tē hag.
\rf Lkn.Qat.095
\tv Gēē 'n hag jērē va#van #
\rf Lkn.Qat.096
\tv “Eh! (i) vä nen̄ ēn van tē 'ät'ät avōh! Too tē van lēh!”
\rf Lkn.Qat.097
\tv Ēn van sēwēl hōw, qis manreg mon pō, tē row vēgēn hag makē ram̄os, tē hag.
\rf Lkn.Qat.098
\tv Gēē 'n mäkä va#van m̄ērē nen̄, gēē vata pah ēn van.
\nt actual text = /gēē 'n wokēm va–van/
\rf Lkn.Qat.099
\tv Alē, Qat woo mētēn i / (haha tan̄ro nen̄ i Qasval) Qasval woo 'n haghag.
\rf Lkn.Qat.100
\tv Wōrō 'n hag va#van, naw tē 'ät avōh, wōrō tē räkäs.
\rf Lkn.Qat.101
\tv Räkäs mongēē wälwäl nen̄, Qat gēn tē mäkä to sa nē ok a to jen nē.
\nt actual text = /tē mäkä to sala nē ga to' jen nē/
\rf Lkn.Qat.102
\tv Nē 'n häläqäg tägäh m̄ērē heg, Tan̄ro tē row tuwoo nē.
\nt actual text = /tē row pulokem nē/ = blockem
\ta xxx
\rf Lkn.Qat.103
\tv Nē tē wähä Tan̄ro mēn too qet ga tutun, Tan̄ro tē häläqäg kēl talvōn um, nē
tē häläqäg talvōn.
\nt /wähä/ = yim = stonem
\rf Lkn.Qat.104
\tv Va#van, we tē wähä kere vata nagē Tan̄ro nen̄ mēn too qet ga tutun we nē tē
ginteg.
\rf Lkn.Qat.105
\tv Ginteg hōw nen̄, tuutuan pah nok makē ram̄os.
\pc *
\rf Lkn.Qat.106
\tv Nē tē row vēgēn hag, nē gēn tē luwluw gēn ek, sa: “Mok ram̄os! Na a marēs
nēk a rēg! Nēk a vutgi!”
\rf Lkn.Qat.107
\tv We ram̄os nen̄ tē rēg, tē vutgi ajew.
\rf Lkn.Qat.108
\tv Gēē tē vēgēn suusuu. Tan̄ro tē vēgēn suusuu gēē ma. 
\rf Lkn.Qat.109
\tv Gēē 'n vēgēn vēgēn va#n, Qat sa: “Mok ram̄os! Nēk rēg, nēk vutgi lēh hag!”
\rf Lkn.Qat.110
\tv Ram̄os nen̄ tē vutgi sa tē vutgi kakaran̄kē vata hag, hag nen̄ to lē pōlō.
\rf Lkn.Qat.111
\tv Gēē 'n jēn̄ hag nen̄, sa “Ha'ēh! Mok ram̄os! Nēk ēt kaōl!”
\rf Lkn.Qat.112
\tv We 'n ram̄os nen̄ tē kaōl.
\rf Lkn.Qat.113
\tv Kaōl kaōl kaōl va#van, jēn̄ hōw lē vanō nen̄, nē tē häläqäg jen, tuutuan tē
häläqäg (jen), nē tē gih lekteg uhli ram̄os nen̄.
\rf Lkn.Qat.114
\tv Tan̄ro nen̄ ēn kakal ma, va rigtäg we: nē tē ukäg ram̄os, ram̄os tē 'äqä wutä i
Qasval.
\rf Lkn.Qat.115
\tv Tē 'äqä wutä Tan̄ro nen̄: sēv lōk lēh ma Lakon.
\rf Lkn.Qat.116
\tv We i Qat, mēn tuutuan, tē haghag Vanōlav.
\pc * 
\pc *  *
\rf Lkn.Qat.117
\tv Suusuu ēn pah woo to heg, Tan̄ro tē mät.
\rf Lkn.Qat.118
\tv Gēē tē hag lōk lēh lē mongēē vanō ok gēē ok ēn row jen ēhē.
\rf Lkn.Qat.119
\tv Nē gēn woo, mok suusuu.
\nl Last question >> They got to Gaua, in Losalav ~ Namasari.

