\sum How two twin boys accidentally created the great Lake of Gaua.
\in Sur la montagne de Gaua, une veuve avait deux jumeaux. Un jour elle se rend au jardin, et leur interdit de
regarder sous son lit.
\in Mais les enfants jouent aux billes (jēn̄jēn̄) et finissent par soulever l'oreiller.  Soudain de l'eau jaillit de
sous son lit!
\in Depuis le jardin la vieille femme comprend ce qui s'est passé, court pour tenter d'enrayer la catastrophe,
mais c'est trop tard: l'inondation submerge tout, et devient le Lac de Gaua.
\in Elle-même saute dans le lac, et se transforme en rocher. On l'appelle Rotung.
\nt
\gl Mythe
\sta Eng-trans_yes
\sta intro_no
\sta synkro_yes
\ord 02

\rf Lkn.Origine.Lac.01
\tv Too magte nē 'n lä too jaajun avan hag nen̄, Makē Gäräs.
\ta Once upon a time, a woman married a man from up there, from Mount Ghäräs.
\rf Lkn.Origine.Lac.02
\tv Taem nē 'n sinän, mon m̄eerat tē mät. Mon m̄eerat ēn mät, gamtō nen̄ tē lä
natōn la nē ok woo m̄ahgen.
\ta While she was pregnant, her husband died. And because he had died, the woman
was left alone to give birth.
\rf Lkn.Origine.Lac.03
\tv Natōn nen̄, m̄eem̄eerat nirō. Tē ätä tuwoo wōrō.
\ta She gave birth to two boys. And she began to bring them up.
\rf Lkn.Origine.Lac.04
\tv Ätä tuwoo wōrō va—van, wōrō tē rēgrēg –
\ta So she brought them up for years and years, and the two boys grew up.
\rf Lkn.Origine.Lac.05
\tv Rēgrēg nen̄ we, on too qēn̄, tēlēē tē hag to, nē tē vis mēn mon wēēwēē
miimiini nen̄ sa: “Na tē van to lē karen.
\nt corrected /karen/  > /lē m̄as/
\ta One day, as they were big boys, the three of them were together, and their mother
said to her children: “I am going to the garden.
\rf Lkn.Origine.Lac.06
\tv La gamuu ga haghag, gamuu wōn jēn̄jēn̄ moomuu jēn̄ la, moomuu jēn̄ wōn a
van lē mok qätä vēē, gamuu mētē lälä lee!
\ta As for you two, you stay here. Now beware: if you play your marble game, if one of
your shell marbles rolls over to my bedhead, then you must not pick it up!
\rf Lkn.Origine.Lac.07
\tv On mok qaatō vēē nen̄, too naha tē hag to van nen̄.”
\ta For under my bedhead, there's something very special.”
\rf Lkn.Origine.Lac.08
\tv Wōrō tē jēn̄ gēn ek. 
\nt noté /gēn nek/, corrige en /gēn ek/ d'après tout le reste du corpus  [08/2010]
\ta So they began to play marbles with their shells. 
\rf Lkn.Origine.Lac.09
\tv Jēn̄ jēn̄ jēn̄ va–van, jēn̄ mon too nen̄ tē van laln̄i (nan) pela mon monwōrō
mama nen̄.
\nt /pela/ < pillow
\ta They played on and on and on – but suddenly one of their marbles rolled all the way
to under their mother's bedhead.
\rf Lkn.Origine.Lac.10
\tv To gēn nen̄, m̄o nen̄ nē tē vis mun nē sa: “E, Tahik! Nēk ēt lä ma mok jēn̄ laln̄ē
nan pilo mon monwōjō mama nen̄!”
\nt noté /gēnen̄/, corrige en /gēn nen̄/ d'après tout le reste du corpus  [08/2010]
\ta At this point, the elder boy exclaimed: “Hey, little brother! Go and get my marble
under Mum's pillow over there! ”
\rf Lkn.Origine.Lac.11
\tv Tahēn nen̄ sa “O, Tuak! Na a lä ēs avōh, monwōjō mama ok ēn suu tuwoo
wōjō sa wōjō a lä avōh; sa wōjō wōn jēn̄jēn̄, la 'n jēn̄ wōn van laln̄ē vēē mon
monwōjō mama, wōjō a lä ēs avōh. Too naha ok van nen̄.”
\ta “What, brother?!” replied the younger one. “I won't go. You know our Mum has
forbidden us to pick it up! She said that if we played marbles, and if a marble rolled
under her bed, we should not go and get it. Because there's something under
there.”
\rf Lkn.Origine.Lac.12
\tv Nē sa “Oh, ta, ga wē woo! Nēk ēt lä ma, °nen̄° va luwluw woo! Luwluw va woo
nen̄!”
\ta “No, no, that's fine!” retorted the other one. “Those were just words. Come on, go
and get it!”
\pc *
\rf Lkn.Origine.Lac.13
\tv Nē 'n turag vata hag m̄ērē heg, nē 'n lan̄ ajew pilo (mon /) laln̄ē vēē mon mon
mama m̄ērē heg, m̄alan ēn row woo we, tun̄ ti vil!
\ta So up he went, and he began to lift up the pillow and mat on his mother's bed like
this. To his great surprise, he suddenly saw some water begin to flow!
\rf Lkn.Origine.Lac.14
\tv Tun̄ ēn vil vata m̄ērē heg, mon mama tē hag to lē karen.
\ta When the water began to flow, his mother was still in the garden.
\rf Lkn.Origine.Lac.15
\tv Mon mama ēn ron̄ vata m̄ērē heg, nē 'n ginteg sēwēl ma, ginteg ma ginteg ma
ginteg ma m̄ērē heg va–van, nē sa: “Awah! Wēē natnatuk ēn qiseg na!”
\ta As soon as she realised what was happening, she ran back down, ran and ran and ran
as fast as she could. “Good heavens!” she said, “My boys have done something
wrong!”
\rf Lkn.Origine.Lac.16
\tv Ginteg ma m̄ērē heg la, nē 'n tuu tuwoo ätägäh vala tun̄ m̄ērē heg la, nē a
wokem ēsavōh we;
\nt tant pis, laisse tomber
\ta And as she was running, she tried to stand in the way of the water, like this, but
could not stop it from flowing. 
\rf Lkn.Origine.Lac.17
\tv nē sa “Awah, wēē natnatuk! Gamuu 'n qiseg nok na! Nek gēn wēē viivirin̄ ga
wēwē, tun̄ ēn van nok mē, la nawnawon woo!”
\ta “Oh boys!” she thought “You've really done me wrong! But now this is too late. The
water has flown away, there's nothing more that can be done.”
\rf Lkn.Origine.Lac.18
\tv Magte nen̄ ēn häläqäg vata m̄ērē heg, nē 'n van nē 'n hag suu vata hōw roka
nen̄ a Liwsal, nek gēn too vat gēn ek vaan inen̄, hahan Rotun̄.
\nt naoia wan ston
\ta The woman jumped in the water, and sat down there in the middle of the flow, up in
Liwsal. Exactly at the place of a rock down there, called Rotung (‘River Woman’).
\rf Lkn.Origine.Lac.19
\tv Vat avan / Vat, magte ok ēn häläqäg maken. 
\ta This rock is no other than this old woman, who had jumped in the water.
\rf Lkn.Origine.Lac.20
\tv Nan vat tun̄ ok tē sēv to maken nen̄, vat ok vaan nen̄ hahan Rotun̄.
\ta That rock's the one hit by the waterfall; that is the rock we call Rotung.
\rf Lkn.Origine.Lac.21
\tv Suusuu nen̄ tē pah gēn van nen̄ le.
\ta And this is how the story ends.

