\rf Mrl.Gaua.01
\tv Rën, rën vita, se nē, rav ta Lakon ker nu-togtog se nē ker ti valgear tea sean be
legleg be tëdun.
\ta A long time ago, the people of Gaua only lived a basic life; they did not know how to
wed.
\rf Mrl.Gaua.02
\tv Kan nen ker so-togtog ker se-legleg be matwon̄ar tabe tenkē.
\ta At that time, the only kind of union they used to have was with forked branches
from trees.
\rf Mrl.Gaua.03
\tv Lakan nen në-tëdun tuwel ta N̄wēw ti sel mē mak tabea, ti sōw sar a Gō.
\ta One day, a man arrived from the island of Maewo. He had drifted at sea, on a large
piece of wood, and had landed on Gaua.
\rf Mrl.Gaua.04
\tv Lakan nen ti matanear se nē iker so-togtog, kan nen na-n̄warat se nē iker
se-legleg be matn̄ar;
\ta As he observed the natives, he realised that men here only formed unions with tree
forks;
\rf Mrl.Gaua.05
\tv nan kan nen, ere vet vavean ker nu-tog gom n̄wer ē.
\ta as for women, they just lived like that.
\pc *
\rf Mrl.Gaua.06
\tv Lakan nen i tëdun ta N̄wēw ma-matanear lan nen ti, ti werēr si *si kan nen*
“ne-legleg kan ti n̄wer-ē tea; ne-legleg lēkē n̄wer-kēkē.”
\ta When he saw that, he told them: “That's not what marriage is like. I'll show what
proper marriage is.”
\rf Mrl.Gaua.07
\tv Lakan nen, se nē i tëdun ta N̄wēw sean ti vōtnōr.
\ta So the man from Maewo began to teach them.
\rf Mrl.Gaua.08
\tv Ti lē seag na-vavean ta Lakon lakan nen, ti leg bēn.
\nt kē ni-lep hag (?) na-lqōvēn t-Alkon nen en, ...
\ta He took one of the native women of Gaua, and married her.
\rf Mrl.Gaua.09
\tv Ti se nen ti, ti leg bēn, na-vavean sean ti wotoktok, karar ga vawot sa nen
nō-lōn̄wēr.
\ta Then he married another one. This woman got pregnant, and gave birth to a boy.
\rf Mrl.Gaua.10
\tv Lakan sa nen iker ga mata, lakan sa nē iker ga valgear si “Ao Surwea! Kisean
nen i/ kisean ni / ne-legleg lēkē n̄wer kēlkē.”
\ta As the people saw this, they began to realise “Oh yes, that's true! *That* is the
proper way to wed.”
\rf Mrl.Gaua.11
\tv Lakan nen sean iker re mel n̄warat qer leg mi re vet vavean.
\ta That's when the men began to form unions with the women.
\rf Mrl.Gaua.12
\tv Lakan nen se nē qer vawot se nē gēn re tëdun.
\ta And that's also when they started to give birth to children.
\rf Mrl.Gaua.13
\tv Nan kan an̄wo vita, lan sen ker ti legleg tea be tëdun, sean ker nu-leg gom be
matwon̄ar tabe tenkē.
\ta Before that, unions were not formed there among people, but with forks from the
trees.
\rf Mrl.Gaua.14
\tv N̄ealkan gom. Bas lakan eē.
\ta That's it. My story's finished.

