\rf Num.Wenawon2.01
\tv Kekkeom.
\ta A story.
\rf Num.Wenawon2.02
\tv Tuar qōn̄ nen, Wenagon mēlē vaten iasan vaten ra nutnutun.
\ta Once upon a time, Wenagon was with his wife and his children.
\rf Num.Wenawon2.03
\tv Nir me sasa vavvan nen, nir tov van be dēdē n̄a.
\ta They were living like that, until one day they went to gather canarium almonds.
\rf Num.Wenawon2.04
\tv Nēr me an sa, Wenagon tov dē.
\ta So they walked up there, and Wenagon began to climb.
\rf Num.Wenawon2.04
\tv Wenagon me dē sa, ti vus ti n̄a vavan, ma ni me tēr mēstēm tuar kariv n̄a ni
tov so.
\ta He climbed up the tree, knocking down bundles of almonds as he went up.
Suddenly, as he tried to grab a branch, he missed, and fell.
\rf Num.Wenawon2.05
\tv Ni me so ror nen ma, ni tov mat.
\ta He fell down on the ground, and died.
\rf Num.Wenawon2.06
\tv Ni me mat, nir tov le ni, sesen̄ ni a vere, gil mataqen nir tov tuvun ni.
\nt /sesen̄/  < *sasaŋ-i  cf. MTP /hah/
\ta When they realised he was dead, they lifted him up, carried him to the village, dug a
grave and buried him.
\rf Num.Wenawon2.07
\tv Tuvun ni, a le qōn̄, ma ni tov tavraket a le mataqen nen,
\ta But after they buried him that night, suddenly he rose again from his grave,
\rf Num.Wenawon2.07
\tv ni tov van abe vuvur nam-nēr, vus mamētē tuar wutve, tov sivtē ni ale
mataqen nen sa nir me tuvun ni allon, wa #
\nt cf. /sivtē net/ = suwyeg qen
\ta he walked to their property, killed a pig, and threw it in the grave he had been
buried in.
\rf Num.Wenawon2.08
\tv Sivtē ror wutve en allon, ni tov to den abe na-veran nen, ni tov to ti ale tuar
vere. Ni tov sasa aben.
\ta So he left the pig down in the grave, and walked away from his place – until he
reached another village where he decided to stay.
\rf Num.Wenawon2.09
\tv Sa ti abe vere nen wa nir mēlē abe u tuar vere en, nir ve mōrōs te da tuar
telvun̄.
\ta One day, the people from that village, together with those of the other village,
decided to organise a big celebration.
\rf Num.Wenawon2.10
\tv Ma nir tov da telvun̄ en, ni tov / tawa namun mēlē tov van ma.
\ta So there was going to be a big party, where his wife was going to come.
\rf Num.Wenawon2.11
\tv Wa tawa namun en, ni te sa ti, ni te kere gor ti u wutve nen a le u mataqen; ni
ve dōm si Wenagon nen wa # wa Wenagon ve to vata.
\nt (elle croyait qu'il s'agissait de W.);  /ve tov vata/ = ???  ou plutōt /ve to vata/ 's'était déjà enfui'??
\ta Meanwhile, his wife in her village had seen the pig in the grave, yet she thought it
was Wenagon himself. She had no idea Wenagon had in fact gone.
\rf Num.Wenawon2.12
\tv Ni te kere gor ti u wutve en va#van, wutve en me dar, ni ve dōm si Wenagon
wa, ni tov le qut wutve en, sun̄un ale get. Tov vatoko gor wev.
\nt /va toko/ 'aller suspendre' ?? --> non car */va/ ou préfixe factitif /va-toko/?
\ta She kept an eye on the pig for a while, and once the body was decomposed, she
took the pig's skull – convinced it was Wenagon's head. She put it in a basket, which
she hung over her fireplace. 
\rf Num.Wenawon2.13
\tv Vatoko gor wev tan̄ nen wa nir tov sasa vavan, din̄ ave u wasin̄in nen tabe nir
ve-da telvun̄ aben nen, nir tov lak. 
\ta After she hung the basket like that, a few days went by, until that moment when
people organised that celebration in the village, with dances. 
\rf Num.Wenawon2.14
\tv Nir te lak ti a le qōn̄. Nir te lak ti a le qōn̄ ma tov nir te lak ti u mavto.
\ta There were going to be dances at night – of those merry dances we called mavto,
which villagers dance all night long.
\rf Num.Wenawon2.15
\tv Ma nir te lak ti, tawa namun en tov lak ma. Lak ran ma tan̄ nen, ma Wenagon
mēlē tov lak ma.
\ta As the dance fired up, the man's wife joined in. She joined in the dance, and so did
Wenagon!
\rf Num.Wenawon2.16
\tv Lak ma tan̄ nen, taem ruru ve rivrivtē ruru, Wenagon wa: “Qut wuruk ve sun̄un
ale get!”
\ta In the middle of the dance, when they stepped closer to each other, Wenagon
exclaimed “It's just a sow's head in your basket!”
\rf Num.Wenawon2.17
\tv Ma nir tov lak mēlē.
\ta And on they danced.
\rf Num.Wenawon2.18
\tv Lak mēlē va#van ma ni tov vit mēlē min tawa namun wa “Qut wuruk ve sun̄un
ale get!”
\ta They danced on and on, until he exclaimed again to his wife “It's just a sow's head in
your basket!”
\rf Num.Wenawon2.19
\tv Tawa namun nen te ron̄ote gor ti.
\ta The woman suddenly strained her ears.
\rf Num.Wenawon2.20
\tv Ni te ron̄ote gor ti, ale namun dōdōmi, ni wa “Sē wun te luwluw ti min na tan̄
ne? Mēstēm Wenagon wun e!”
\ta She heard his call, and thought “Who could be talking to me like that? It sounds like
my Wenagon!?”
\rf Num.Wenawon2.21
\tv Nir tov lak mēlē ma tan̄ ne, taem ni me vit ran mēlē si “Qut wuruk ve sun̄un
ale get!”,
\ta The dance started again and went on, until she heard once again “It's just a sow's
head in your basket!”
\rf Num.Wenawon2.22
\tv ma tawa namun tov waw ran ameken; ma ni tov vit min ni wa “Wenagon, nik
te karan̄ke ti!”
\ta This time, the woman called back in reply; and then she added “Wenagon! You really
are a crazy man!”
\rf Num.Wenawon2.23
\tv Ma kekeom en me bas aben ne wa.
\ta And this is how my story ends.

