\rf Drg.Wrisris.01
\tv Seg o susrig nami Wrisris. M̄rag igēn va-mrōs so-ron̄ o susrig nami Wrisris.
\tf Voici l'histoire de Wrisris. Car c'est bien cette histoire que tu souhaitais entendre.
\ta °°Here comes the real story of Wrisris. The story of Wrisris, just like we like to hear
it.
\nl SUSRIG!!  not susrig blemraw!!  cf. BG4-10b
\rf Drg.Wrisris.03
\tv Susrig nami Wrisris ni gēn m-van tm̄e seg.
\tf L'histoire de Wrisris commence comme ceci.
\ta The story of Wrisris goes like this.
\rf Drg.Wrisris.04
\tv Wrisris, ni m-togtog a Bētās, gin tuar wasn̄in a Diwtag.
\tf Ce Wrisris habite sur le grand lac Letas, plus précisément à Diwtag.
\ta Wrisris lives on the lake Betaas, in a place called Diwtagh.
\nl present or past?
\rf Drg.Wrisris.05
\tv Namon o tne togtog a Diwtag.
\ta Yes, the name of his place is Diwtagh.
\tf L'endroit exact où il habite s'appelle Diwtag.
\rf Drg.Wrisris.06
\tv Wrisris, ni tuar o tdun vi-lwo soqsoq namikma, vat a Lkon.
\ta Wrisris is a highly significant figure for us, on Gaua.
\tf Wrisris, c'est une personnalité majeure pour nous, les gens de Gaua.
\rf Drg.Wrisris.07
\tv Ni o tdun vi-lwo rōw kma t-var ti kak ni o tawri mlēg.
\ta He’s one of those major personalities we call “Above the Sky”.
\tf Les personnages importants de son genre, nous les appelons “Au-delà des Nuages”.
\rf Drg.Wrisris.08
\tv Ni va-lwo rōw sāl bas ratle o tdun vat a Lkon.
\ta He is the most important personality of Gaua.
\ng obviously /rōw/ serves as intensifier for /lwo/.
\tf Il dépasse largement en renommée tous les autres individus de Gaua.
\pc *
\rf Drg.Wrisris.09
\tv O susrig nami Wrisris wor, nēk nēk t-tog ti le mram gēn dek, nēk le mon̄ o
vre, m̄rag kma a Lkon; 
\ta Here’s what we say about Wrisris. Let’s say you’re alive in this world, living in your
country just like we live here on Gaua. 
\nq /nēk t-tog ti le mram/? or /nēk t-tog t’ le mram/??
\ng Predicative locative: /nēk le mon̄ o vre/
\tf Or, voici ce qu'on raconte sur Wrisris. Supposons que toi, tu es encore de ce monde, et
que tu vis dans ta contrée, comme nous ici à Gaua… 
\rf Drg.Wrisris.09
\tv nēk va-mrōs s-ron̄ tavul kak i savin̄ m-mat, i tuan̄ le i tman̄, nēk va-mrōs
so-vrēgēl, kak i tman̄ m-mat sur sav, nēk so-van tek i Wrisris.
\nq should be /nēk s-van tek/ ?!
\ta Now suppose you wanted to understand about the death of one of your relatives –
say, your brother or your father. If you want to know, say, the reason why your
father died, then you should go see Wrisris.
\tf Imaginons que quelqu'un de ta famille est décédé, un de tes frères ou bien ton père. Eh
bien, si tu désires savoir de quoi exactement cette personne est décédée, il faut que tu
ailles voir Wrisris.
\rf Drg.Wrisris.10
\tv Nēk s-van sag, nēk s-la o qo sutwal, o qo ve-wed, nēk s-van sag sur i Wrisris,
nēk ron̄: “Na va-mrōs nēk s-van ma na, sur na va-mrōs s-tek i tmāk, le i tsik.
Ni m-mat sa, na so-vrēgēl tēmē ak ni m-mat ni o sm̄an le… sē m-wōr ni.”
\ta When you go up there, don't forget to take one pig, one white pig. When you go in
and meet Wrisris, you'll say: “I'd like you to come with me, because I want to see my
father, or my brother. He just died, but I don't know whether he was just sick, or
whether someone used black sorcery against him.”
\tf Avant de te mettre en chemin, munis-toi d'un cochon, un cochon blanc. Puis lorsque tu
verras Wrisris, explique-lui bien: “Je souhaiterais que tu me conduises jusqu'à mon père, ou
mon frère. Je sais qu'il est mort, mais je ne sais pas s'il est mort de maladie ou bien… si
quelqu'un lui a jeté un mauvais sort.”
\rf Drg.Wrisris.11
\tv Wrisris m-la nēk kmur so van gin tuar namon o wasn̄in, ni s-wōt o nge o gtam
vat aē kmur s-van.
\ta Wrisris then takes you to his den. Opens the door, and your trip begins.
\tf Wrisris t'emmène ensuite jusqu'à son antre # il en ouvre la porte, c'est alors que votre voyage
commence.
\rf Drg.Wrisris.12
\tv Kmur s-van, tog nēk va-vavgat min i Wrisris, i Wrisris to-vavgat wor ti.
\ta As you walk together, don't say anything to Wrisris; only he is allowed to talk.
\rf Drg.Wrisris.13
\tv M̄rag Wrisris m-vit min nēk ron̄: “Dār m-van wa, nēk m-tek wa, na me-ttan̄
gin tuar tdun dēn nēr gēn nen̄, i tman̄ gēn nen̄ le.
\ta Then Wrisris might say something like: “As we walk together, watch me. When I
touch someone from among the people over there, that will be your father.
\rf Drg.Wrisris.14
\tv Ti dār qra ron̄ sē ka, i tman̄ nen̄ va-sav, ni m-mat wor ni o sm̄an, le… sē m-wōr
ni?”
\ta Then you and I will try to hear from your father what happened to him: did he die
of sickness, or of black sorcery?”
\rf Drg.Wrisris.15
\tv Dār s-vanvan, tuar tdun s-van tētēg Wrisris dār s-van avvan, van sag, van sag
le qarn̄a tan.
\nl pronoun mixup here:  yumi2 was Wrisris + you;  becomes narrator + you.
\ta So you and I walk on, one of us is ready to follow Wrisris. We walk on and on,
further and further inwards into the depths of the earth.
\rf Drg.Wrisris.15
\tv Tuar o wasn̄in allon nēr me va m̄rag o gvur. Tdun ve-mmat gēs aē.
\ta Deep inside there, is a place which was built like a house. The abode of the Dead.
\rf Drg.Wrisris.16
\tv Wrisris so-ttan̄ gin sē nen̄, i tman̄ gēn sa le.
\ta Should Wrisris lay his hand on someone, that will be your father.
\rf Drg.Wrisris.17
\tv Tman̄ sa ni m-mat wor ni o sm̄an. E ni so mōl kēl.
\ta Your father, say, who will just have died from sickness. So he will go back.
\pc *  *
\rf Drg.Wrisris.18
\tv Nēr so tog a-vre avvan, tuar sē kak i ntōn m-sem̄ le m-mat, so van tek mlē
Wrisris.
\ta People will live in the village, on and on, until one day someone – say, someone's
child – falls sick, or dies. It'll be time to go see Wrisris again.
\rf Drg.Wrisris.19
\tv Dār s-van sē, nēk s-vosnāg i ntuk sa m-mat wa ni m-mat ni o sm̄an, le sē
m-wōr ni?
\nt /vosnāg/ = montrer
\ta We'd go again so you can show him my son who died, and understand whether he
just died of sickness, or of black sorcery.
\nl weird person reference!
\rf Drg.Wrisris.20
\tv Rār s-van, s-van sag, i Wrisris so-ttan̄ ron̄ “I ntōn̄ gēn sa le!”
\ta So the two would walk in, deeper and deeper inside, until Wrisris touches someone
and says “Here’s your child!”
\rf Drg.Wrisris.21
\tv S-vārus nēr “M̄erm̄er sa m-mat ma, m-daksa? O sm̄an wor, le # sē m-wōr ni?”
# “Obek, ni m-mat ma sala, tuar tdun a-vre m-wōr ni.”
\ta He'd ask them “This boy who just died, what happened to him? Was it just sickness,
or was it sorcery?” – “Oh no (they'll answer), he just died because someone in the
village killed him with sorcery.”
\rf Drg.Wrisris.22
\tv Sē nen̄ s-mōl kēl, s-mōl ror nen̄ a-vre, s-wōr bas o / nēr o tarn̄i tdun sa nēr ka
t-tog t' a-vre sa nēr ka m-wōr o m̄erm̄er nen̄. S-wōr bas nēr.
\ta Now that man will come back out, walk back all the way to the village, and start
casting spells on all the descendants of the villager who had killed his boy. He will
wipe them out.
\rf Drg.Wrisris.23
\tv Le tektek namikma, o wōr, o tdun a Lkon m-bas gin a Bētās.
\ta In our view, black sorcery, that was the reason why the people from Gaua
disappeared, around the Betaas lake.
\rf Drg.Wrisris.24
\tv Sē s-mat a-vre, s-van sag s-vārus Wrisris, ron̄ kak m-wōr ni ni s-mōl kēl ma
a-vre ni s-wōr bas o tdun.
\ta Should somebody die in the village, people would walk up to ask Wrisris. Then if it
turned out it was sorcery, they would come back to the village and cast spells back
on everyone.
\pc *  *  *
\rf Drg.Wrisris.25
\tv La i Wrisris ni t-tog ti, nēk o m̄erat nēk m-van tek ni sag, ni o m̄erat. 
\ta The way Wrisris is, if you are a man and walk in to see him, he will be a man.
\rf Drg.Wrisris.26
\tv La kak nēk o rqa kak nēk va-mrōs tek Wrisris / nēk s-van sag nēk s-tek Wrisris,
nēk s-van sag, nēk o rqa, ni o rqa.
\ta But if you are a woman, and you want to meet Wrisris, as you walk in to see him, as
soon as you walk in, if you're a woman, Wrisris will be a woman too.
\rf Drg.Wrisris.27
\tv La i Wrisris, ni s-vanvan dēn̄ le vre le vara Wetman. Ni va-vrēgēl Wetman,
Wetman va-vrēgēl ni.
\ta Wrisris often travels to the country of Westerners. He knows Westerners, and
Westerners know him.
\rf Drg.Wrisris.28
\tv Wetman s-in̄ḡlēs min ni, Wrisris so-vgat tma-kma / tma-gēn min ni.
\ta Should a Westerner speak English to him, Wrisris will reply to him in our language.
\rf Drg.Wrisris.29
\tv Kma t-var ti ron̄ so-vgat tma-kma, vgat o lē vatmagēn, Wetman t-ron̄ tavul ti.
\nq /o le/??
\ta As legend has it, he can speak like us, speak our language, and Westerners will
understand everything.
\rf Drg.Wrisris.30
\tv Wrisris, tuar qōn̄ nēk s-van sag, nēk m-tek ni t-gāngēn ti, ngan o vivni o
vrin̄rin̄ aē wa, vni tin mās, le vni tin mit, ni t-van tek t' a le vre vi-lwo, le vara
Wetman.
\ta Wrisris, if one day you walk up and see him having a meal, you may be able to see
leftovers from fish tins, or meat tins: that's because he keeps travelling all the way
to the big continent, to the country of Westerners.
\rf Drg.Wrisris.31
\tv Nēk so-vrēgēl tēmē kak ni t-van aksav ti, sur Wrisris, ni o wrisris wa.
\nt etymology (folk?) of Wrisris:  the Transformer!   cf. /w-/ + /ris/
\ta You won't be able to know what he's up to, because Wrisris he's a transformer.
\rf Drg.Wrisris.32
\tv Wetman va-mrōs s-tek ni, Wetman ni s-van sag, ni o Wetman.
\ta If a Westerner wants to see him, as he walks in, Wrisris will appear as a Westerner.
\pc *  *
\rf Drg.Wrisris.33
\tv O wrisris ni o tawri mlēg ni t-tog gor namikma o tuar wasn̄in ti, kma t-var ti
kak o Grāt.
\ta This magic Wrisris is one of those figures we call “Above the Sky”. He also watches
over another important place of ours, the volcano we call “Ghraat”.
\rf Drg.Wrisris.34
\tv Ni o tdun vi-lwo namikma.
\ta He's a major figure for us.
\rf Drg.Wrisris.35
\tv La Wrisris, ni m-te mat tēmē attua / attua soqsoq, Wrisris ni qra mat wor ti.
\ta You know, Wrisris did not die a very long time ago. Wrisris died just recently.
\rf Drg.Wrisris.36
\tv Na na to-vavgat t' sa i tbuk vagrō m-van m-tek ni, ni m-mat nēr me-tvig ni. I
tbuk vagrō.
\nt /to-vavgat sa/ >> corrigé en /to-vavgat t' sa/
\ta Even myself, as I am talking right now, I have a great grandfather who went to see
him. And when Wrisris died, he was there at his funeral. My great grandfather.
\rf Drg.Wrisris.37
\tv Avvan, na to-vavgat t' sa sur i tbuk vagrō ni m-tek ni, me-tvig ni.
\ta And here I am now, talking about this great grandfather of mine who met him, who
buried him.
\rf Drg.Wrisris.38
\tv Seg wedek gēn o susrig nami Wrisris.
\ta Such is the story of Wrisris.
\pc *  *  *
\rf Drg.Wrisris.39
\tv Am̄o, ra sul ta Lkon va-vvōr.
\ta In the old days, the island of Gaua had a huge population.
\rf Drg.Wrisris.40
\tv La sur, kak i tsik s-mat, na s-van sag na s-van sur Wrisris, kmār s-van le va nen̄,
Wrisris ron̄: “Tuan̄ gēn sa m-mat le. La nēr / tuar tdun a-vre m-wōr ni.” Na
s-van kēl ma na s-wōr bas nēr o si tdun nen̄.
\nt written /Tuan̄ *gin* sa m-mat le/ > I correct to /gēn/  (2011-12-26)
\ta But then, should my brother die, I'd walk in and go see Wrisris; I'd walk with him to
that place in there, and he'd say “That brother of yours is dead. Someone in the
village killed him.” And then I would immediately come back and kill him with all his
descendants.
\rf Drg.Wrisris.41
\tv M̄rag nēr le gvur sutwal ak nēr # bul-vēs? Bul-san̄vul le #
\ta Imagine how many there were in each family – how many people? ten, perhaps?
\rf Drg.Wrisris.42
\tv Na s-wōr bas nēr nēr s-mat.
\ta But then I'd use sorcery and wipe them all out.
\rf Drg.Wrisris.43
\tv Titi m-daw tm̄a a Lkon sa, dek gēn nēk s-tek tm̄a Lkon sa, tm̄a s-vēs wor nok.
\ta And this is how here on Gaua, if you look around here on Gaua, you can see there
aren't many people left.
\rf Drg.Wrisris.44
\tv Dek gēn t-bon̄ galāg gēn nok dek ti. Am̄o, m-van ma o tdun obek.
\ta Well, right now, we have come back to a decent number. But before this, we had
reached a point where people had almost disappeared.
\rf Drg.Wrisris.46
\tv Sur o wōr gēn sa le.
\ta And the reason for this was black sorcery.
\rf Drg.Wrisris.47
\tv Na s-van sag na s-vārus, m-mat wor mi o sm̄an, va-wē.
\ta For if I walked in and enquired, if it turned out the death was just due to sickness,
that was fine.
\rf Drg.Wrisris.48
\tv La kak m-wōr, ti na s-van kēl ma na s-wōr kēl ra sē sa ka nēr ka m-wōr na / Na
s-ram kēl wor ra titsik nen̄ sa nēr ka m-wōr ni.
\nt belle relative clause!
\ta But then if it was sorcery, then I'd come back and cast spells back on those who had
killed me / I'd avenge my brother who was murdered that way.
\rf Drg.Wrisris.49
\tv Vetm̄e dek gēn le.
\ta That's how it was.
\pc *  *  *
\rf Drg.Wrisris.50
\tv Tawe tdun a Lkon sa, m-bas. Nēr (ka) m-mat bas.
\ta Many people died on this island of Gaua.  They all disappeared.
\rf Drg.Wrisris.52
\tv Me-qtēg aē sa, m-van tm̄e seg, van walōg Lkon.
\ta It started one day, and then went on and on all around the island.
\rf Drg.Wrisris.53
\tv Nēk s-van a Lkon sa nēk s-tek o tētne gvur olbaot, le m̄ōs, sur kēlkēl sur le m̄ōs
sa, nēk s-tek o tētne vre sur le m̄ōs gēs sēg, o tdun t-aē gēn nen̄ m-mat bas le.
\ta If you walk around Gaua, you'll see remains of houses everywhere in the bush; if you
follow the traces in the bush, you'll see traces of entire villages scattered around:
those were the people who disappeared in those times.
\rf Drg.Wrisris.54
\tv La m-van ma aqri, ti dek gēn tm̄a t-bon̄ galāg kēl ti.
\ta Nowadays it's different, our numbers have picked up again a little.
\rf Drg.Wrisris.55
\tv La am̄o va, o tdun m-bas nok.
\ta But in the past, we did go through massive losses.
\pc *  *  *
\rf Drg.Wrisris.56
\tv Wrisris sa, ni m-togtog mumul.
\ta Wrisris lived for a long time.
\rf Drg.Wrisris.57
\tv Ni me-tger a Bētās, le mon o vre. Ni m-mat wor srēg ka, ni me-tmarga, ni so
mat.
\ta He passed away by lake Betaas, where he had lived. He just died a natural death: he
had become old, and then he died.
\rf Drg.Wrisris.58
\tv La ni m-tog ni m-tog ni m-tog mumul. O taw va-bon̄ va-bon̄ soqsoq.
\ta But before that, he had lived for a very, very long time. For many many years.
\rf Drg.Wrisris.60
\tv O tdun t-wotwot wōn wor ni ti, t-mat ti, Wrisris t-tog ti.
\ta For generations and generations, Wrisris was present when people were born, and
still present when they died.
\rf Drg.Wrisris.61
\tv Avvan, ni m-tog avvan, me-tmarga rōrōw ni so mat.
\ta He lived all this time, for very very long, until he became so old that he finally passed
away.
\rf Drg.Wrisris.62
\tv Ni so mat, ratle tdun wedwed, m-van nok ma.
\ta He died at a time when white people had already come here.
\rf Drg.Wrisris.63
\tv Ra dōn t-van dēn̄ t' gin ni.
\ta Some of them even had visited him personally.
\pc *
\rf Drg.Wrisris.64
\tv Tuar qōn̄, nēk s-van sag kak ni obek, m̄rag tuar o tdun vi-lwo rōw ka t-tog t'
aē.
\ta Certain days, you would go up and not find him; instead, his place would be taken
by some important chief.
\rf Drg.Wrisris.65
\tv T-van dēn̄ t' gin ni, ron̄ “Ni obek sa! Ni m-van le vara Wetman.”
\ta You'd walk all the way to that chief, who would tell you “Wrisris is not here. He's
gone to the land of the White.”
\rf Drg.Wrisris.66
\tv M̄rag le susrig ka nami Wrisris ron̄, Wrisris dēn̄ ta Ostrelia.
\ta That's a well known story, that Wrisris went all the way to Australia.
\rf Drg.Wrisris.67
\tv Ostrelia arās, Wrisris t-van ti ni t-van aksavm̄ag ti?
\ta Australia is very far, so how could Wrisris even go there?
\rf Drg.Wrisris.68
\tv O plēn obek, sur s-la ni s-van, nēr s-tek tēmē kak ni s-van lul a mke ak.
\ta There was no plane that he could fly in then. And nobody ever saw him on a ship!
\rf Drg.Wrisris.69
\tv Wrisris ni tuar tdun sa # ni o tdun la, tuar qōn̄ ni s-van nēk te tek late ni ni
t-van ti.
\ta That's the sort of person Wrisris was. He was just a man, but some days he would
just become invisible and travel.
\rf Drg.Wrisris.70
\tv Tuar qōn̄ nēr s-van kēl sag nēr s-mōl kēl ma ron̄ “Wrisris m-mōl kēl nok ma!”
\ta And then another day, people would walk back up there, and returning to the
village they'd say “Wrisris is back!”
\pc *  *  *
\rf Drg.Wrisris.71
\tv Wrisris ni ta Lkon, ni m-wot a Lkon: a Mke-Grāt, a tāvtēn t-aē.
\ta Wrisris was from Gaua, he was born on Gaua: on the Ghraat volcano, just
underneath it.
\rf Drg.Wrisris.72
\tv Le qōtgi grāt, o grāt a mken, aa? a tāvtēn t-aē. Namon o tne vre a tāvtēn t-aē.
\ta You see the volcano rising high above, right? well, he was born underneath, at the
foot of the hill. His place is at the foot of the volcano.
\rf Drg.Wrisris.73
\tv Ni s-togtog, nintēg tuar o wasn̄in a Diwtag.
\ta More precisely, he lived in a place called Diwtagh.
\pc *  *
\rf Drg.Wrisris.74
\tv Kulēi Wrisris m-mat / m̄rag kulēi Wrisris m-mat gēn nen̄, tuar tdun so lēs ni.
\ta After the death of Wrisris, right after his death, someone else took his place.
\rf Drg.Wrisris.75
\tv Tuar tdun m-lēs ni sa, na ssan Wedām.
\ta That other person who replaced him was called Wendaam.
\rf Drg.Wrisris.76
\tv Nēk va-mrōs vanvan kēl mlē a Mke-Grāt, dek gēn nēk va-mrōs tek nēr o ratle
tmat, nēk to tek late sur Wrisris m-mat nok.
\ta If you want to walk back in the volcano again to visit the world of Ghosts, it is now
impossible, because Wrisris is dead now.
\rf Drg.Wrisris.77
\tv Ba nēk va-mrōs nēk s-kal wor a Mke-Grāt, nēk s-tek o tuar wasn̄in, o tuar bē sa
kma t-var ti (k)ak o Bē Dōnōm.
\ta But if you want, you can still climb the volcano and go see a different place – a river,
which we call River Donom.
\rf Drg.Wrisris.78
\tv Nēk s-van, Wedām so van ma nēk aē.
\ta If you go there, Wendaam will come with you.
\rf Drg.Wrisris.79
\tv Van ma nēk, s-kal ma nēk sag nēk s-tek o bē.
\ta He'll come with you, take you all the way up so you can see the river.
\rf Drg.Wrisris.80
\tv Bas, nēk so qra sēw kēl ma.
\ta And then you can climb back down.
\rf Drg.Wrisris.81
\tv Tuar bē a mken nen̄, kma t-var ti ron̄ o Bē Dōnōm.
\nt written /a mke nen̄/, I edit to /a mken nen̄/
\ta So that river on top of the volcano, we call it River Donom.
\rf Drg.Wrisris.82
\tv Bē Dōnōm sa, o dōdōm t-aē wor kak nēk m-mat le mram sa, nēk s-van sag,
\ta And this river Donom has a significance of its own. If one day you die in this world
of ours, then you will go up there. 
\rf Drg.Wrisris.82
\tv nēk s-van ror nēk s-sim o bē nen̄, nēk s-sim vagvagē,
\ta You'll go up to the top, and then go down to drink the river's water. That will be the
last thing you drink.
\rf Drg.Wrisris.82
\tv sur na llon̄ s-sil vtē ra tutuan̄ le mram.
\ta Drinking it will make you forget all your loved ones in this world, for ever.

